  "local_port": 56794,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the types of induction motors?",
  "response": "Induction motors are widely used in various applications due to their robustness and simplicity. They can be categorized into several types based on different criteria. Here are the main types of induction motors:\n\n### 1. **Based on the Rotor Design:**\n   - **Squirrel Cage Induction Motor:** \n     - This is the most common type of induction motor. It has a rotor design that consists of laminated iron core with conductors disposed in a manner similar to a squirrel cage. It is robust and requires less maintenance.\n   - **Wound Rotor Induction Motor:**\n     - This type features a rotor with windings connected to external resistors or circuits, allowing for better control of speed and torque. It\u2019s often used in applications requiring high starting torque.\n\n### 2. **Based on the Number of Phases:**\n   - **Single-Phase Induction Motor:**\n     - Typically used for household appliances and small machines. They require a starting mechanism, such as a capacitor or a shaded pole.\n   - **Three-Phase Induction Motor:**\n     - Most commonly used in industrial applications due to their high efficiency and power. They provide continuous torque and are generally more efficient than single-phase motors.\n\n### 3. **Based on Rotor Speed:**\n   - **Synchronous Induction Motor:**\n     - Not technically an induction motor in the strictest sense, but some designs allow for synchronous speed operation. Usually employed in applications requiring precise speed control.\n   - **Asynchronous Motor:**\n     - This is the typical type of induction motor where the rotor speed is less than synchronous speed.\n\n### 4. **Based on the Enclosure:**\n   - **Open-Type Motors:**\n     - These motors are not enclosed and are used in clean environments.\n   - **Closed-Type Motors:**\n     - Enclosed in a protective casing to prevent contamination from dust and moisture.\n   - **Explosion-Proof Motors:**\n     - Designed for hazardous environments where flammable gases or dust may be present.\n\n### 5. **Special Types:**\n   - **Permanent Split Capacitor (PSC) Motor:**\n     - A single-phase motor with a capacitor that improves starting torque and running characteristics.\n   - **Capacitor Start, Capacitor Run Motor:**\n     - Utilizes two capacitors to enhance starting torque and improve efficiency during operation.\n   - **Universal Motor:**\n     - Can operate on both AC and DC supply, commonly used in portable power tools.\n\nThese classifications help in selecting the appropriate induction motor for specific applications based on their operational characteristics, efficiency, and design requirements.",
